# THE PACKAGE -- what we hand people, and the ONLY thing the User Manual may name.
#
# A user gets a zip: the `altairsim` binary, `altairsim-manual.pdf`, `USING-ALTAIRSIM.md`, and
# the examples/ tree -- each example a self-contained folder holding a machine file and the
# media it mounts. The DIR table below is the list of them, and this sentence deliberately
# does not repeat it: naming them twice in one file is how the previous wording ("some disks
# and tapes") outlived the layout it described.
#
# They do NOT get this repository -- no src/, no CMakeLists, no tests, no DESIGN.md, no
# docs/boards/. So the manual may not reference any of it, and every path it prints must be
# a path that exists INSIDE THE ZIP.
#
# TWO documents ship, not one. The manual (a PDF) is for the human. USING-ALTAIRSIM.md is for
# an AI assistant driving the machine over MCP -- it is dropped, verbatim, into a working
# directory so a user can start Claude there and say "Using altairsim, do ...". It is a FILE
# below (token-expanded on the way in, exactly like the manual), NOT a chapter of the manual.
#
# This file is how that is enforced rather than merely intended. It is the single source
# of truth for three things that would otherwise drift apart:
#
#   1. TOKENS. The manual's Markdown writes {{MACHINE_CPM}}, never a literal path. The doc
#      build substitutes from here and FAILS on any token it cannot resolve, so a path
#      cannot reach the PDF unexpanded and a path cannot be invented in prose.
#   2. CONTENTS. tools/build-package.sh assembles the zip from the DIRS and FILES below.
#   3. THE TEST. tests/acceptance/manual.cmake builds that same package, in a directory
#      with no repository in sight, and runs the manual's own commands against it. If a
#      chapter tells you to type something that does not work in the package, it fails.
#
# THE PACKAGE LAYOUT MIRRORS THE REPOSITORY'S examples/ TREE, and that is the point of that
# tree (2026-07-19): the shipped set has ONE home, the tests boot it there, and assembling
# the package is a copy rather than a rearrangement. A path that works in a clone works in
# the zip, which is the only way the manual can be true in both.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# DIRS -- <package path>  <=  <path in this repo>
#
# Each example ships as a DIRECTORY, because a machine file names the disk lying beside
# it ("cpm22b23-56k.dsk", no directory at all) and paths inside a machine file resolve
# against THAT FILE. Keep the .toml and its image together and the folder boots wherever
# it is copied to -- which is the whole point of the rule.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

DIR  examples/cpm        <=  examples/cpm
DIR  examples/basic      <=  examples/basic
DIR  examples/sol        <=  examples/sol
DIR  examples/diskbasic  <=  examples/diskbasic

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# FILES -- <package path>  <=  <path in this repo>
#
# A single file copied to the zip, TOKEN-EXPANDED on the way in (the {{MACHINE_CPM}} in
# USING-ALTAIRSIM.md becomes the real package path, same as in the manual). Use this for a
# loose top-level file; use DIR for a self-contained example folder.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

FILE  USING-ALTAIRSIM.md   <=  docs/USING-ALTAIRSIM.md

# Disk BASIC WAS the TBD here, and it is now real (2026-07-19): an image, a machine file
# and an acceptance test that reaches its OK prompt. The DIR line above is the two lines
# this note said it would take.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# TOKENS -- what the manual writes, and what it means.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# The CP/M machine. Buffered CP/M 2.2 on an 8" floppy: it carries `startup = ["RUN FF00"]`,
# so naming it IS booting it, and it is the quick start.
MACHINE_CPM   = examples/cpm/cpm22-buffered.toml
DISK_CPM      = examples/cpm/cpm22b23-56k.dsk

# Cassette BASIC. WHICH ONE SHIPS IS TBD (4K or 8K); this points at 4K today because it is
# the one with an acceptance test behind it.
MACHINE_BASIC = examples/basic/basic4k.toml
TAPE_BASIC    = examples/basic/4K BASIC Ver 3-1.tap
LOADER_BASIC  = examples/basic/LDR4K31.HEX
NAME_BASIC    = Altair 4K BASIC 3.1

# The Sol-20. Reaches SOLOS's prompt with TREK80 in the cassette deck; the operator types
# `XE TRK80`, because that is input to SOLOS and no machine file can type at a guest.
MACHINE_SOL   = examples/sol/trek80.toml
TAPE_SOL      = examples/sol/TRK80.TAP
WAV_SOL       = examples/sol/TRK80.WAV
NAME_SOL      = TREK80 (Processor Technology, 1977)

# Disk BASIC. Reaches its OK prompt after a five-question startup dialogue, and the second
# question (LINEPRINTER?) takes C, O or Q and re-asks in silence on anything else -- so any
# prose using these tokens has to say so, or it is describing a machine that looks hung.
MACHINE_DISKBASIC = examples/diskbasic/diskbasic.toml
DISK_DISKBASIC    = examples/diskbasic/Disk BASIC 4.1.dsk
NAME_DISKBASIC    = Altair Disk Extended BASIC 4.1
